  "The photoelectric effect, where light ejects electrons from a metal surface, can only be explained by treating light as particles (photons) with energy E = hf, not as waves.": "",
  "The energy of a photon is given by:": "",
  "E = (1/2)mv^2": "",
  "E = qV": "",
  "E = hf": "",
  "E = mc^2": "",
  "The energy of a photon is E = hf = hc/lambda, where h is Planck's constant (6.63 * 10^-34 J*s), f is frequency, and lambda is wavelength.": "",
  "The minimum frequency of light needed to eject electrons from a metal surface is called the:": "",
  "Resonant frequency": "",
  "Critical frequency": "",
  "Threshold frequency": "",
  "Natural frequency": "",
  "The threshold frequency (f0) is the minimum frequency of incident light required to eject electrons from a particular metal surface. Below this frequency, no electrons are emitted regardless of intensity.": "",
  "Increasing the intensity of light above the threshold frequency will:": "",
  "Increase the number of ejected electrons per second": "",
  "Decrease the threshold frequency": "",
  "Change the work function": "",
  "Increase the maximum kinetic energy of ejected electrons": "",
  "Increasing intensity means more photons per second, so more electrons are ejected per second (higher photocurrent). The maximum kinetic energy depends on frequency, not intensity.": "",
  "The photoelectric equation is:": "",
  "KE_max = phi - hf": "",
  "KE_max = hf - phi": "",
  "KE_max = h/f - phi": "",
  "KE_max = hf + phi": "",
  "Einstein's photoelectric equation: KE_max = hf - phi, where hf is the photon energy and phi (work function) is the minimum energy needed to free an electron from the metal surface.": "",
  "The work function of a metal represents:": "",
  "The stopping potential": "",
  "The kinetic energy of ejected electrons": "",
  "The total energy of the photon": "",
  "The minimum energy needed to remove an electron from the metal surface": "",
  "The work function (phi) is the minimum energy required to liberate an electron from the surface of a metal. It depends on the metal and its surface conditions.": "",
