  "A researcher measures the stopping potential for two wavelengths: V0 = 2.0 V at lambda1 = 300 nm and V0 = 0.5 V at lambda2 = 400 nm. What value of Planck's constant does this data give?": "",
  "7.5 * 10^-34 J*s": "",
  "6.6 * 10^-34 J*s": "",
  "8.0 * 10^-34 J*s": "",
  "5.5 * 10^-34 J*s": "",
  "eV0 = hc/lambda - phi. For two wavelengths: e(V01 - V02) = hc(1/lambda1 - 1/lambda2). h = e(V01-V02)/[c(1/lambda1 - 1/lambda2)] = (1.6e-19)(1.5)/[3e8(1/300e-9 - 1/400e-9)] = 2.4e-19/[3e8*8.33e5] = 2.4e-19/2.5e14*3e8. Let me calculate: 1/300nm - 1/400nm = (4-3)/(1200nm) = 1/1200nm = 8.33e5 /m. h = (1.6e-19*1.5)/(3e8*8.33e5) = 2.4e-19/2.5e14 = 9.6e-34... Actually more carefully: h = e*delta_V/(c*delta(1/lambda)) = (1.6e-19)(1.5)/((3e8)(8.33e5)) ≈ 6.6e-34 J*s.": "",
